                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d535">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.90f2/7: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-10-26T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >October 26, 1931—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 26—9:15
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>421. Am informed by Hejazi Minister that his Government has insisted in all
                    treaties so far concluded upon the inclusion of a clause <pb facs="0674" n="554"
                        xml:id="pg_554"/> stating in substance “Arabic and (English) texts shall
                    both be official texts and both have equal value.”</p>
                <p>Hejazi Minister foresees this point will be immediately raised by his Government
                    and to avoid delay asks your concurrence that such a phrase should be inserted
                    in the agreement contemplated in the Department’s 953, October 12, 1931.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
